    <h4 class="articleTitle">Rapid Fire Info</h4>
    <p class="generalText">
        A Virtual Local Area Network (VLAN) is used to segment the network. A VLAN can be access or trunk mode. Access mode supports only one VLAN. Trunk mode supports multiple VLANs. Each port on a switch can be configured to be on a different VLAN.
    </p>
    <p class="generalText">
        The main reason switches are so load is due to the fan size. Switches are usually 1U in size which means that the fans to cool the switch can’t be too big. A smaller fan needs to spin faster to move the same amount of air as a larger fan. The high speed of fan spinning causes a lot of noise. Also, a switch has multiple small fans to keep it cool.
    </p>
    <p class="generalText">
        The Ethernet and SFP ports on a switch can be dual-personality ports. You can use the Ethernet or SFP port, but not both at the same time.
    </p>
    <p class="generalText">
        Switches can be put into stacking mode. Stacking is referring to connecting two or more switches together to act as a single switch. You need a stacking module to stack switches.
    </p>
    <p class="generalText">
        The USB type A port on a switch is used to upgrade the firmware of the switch.
    </p>
    <p class="generalText">
        An unmanaged switch doesn’t need any configuration. This way unmanaged switches can be plug & play. Managed switches need to be configured. Configuration such as turning ports on or off, adding VLANs and etc.
    </p>
    <p class="generalText">
        Switches are designed to use power supply modules that slot into the case of a switch. This way when the power supply fails you can easily remove and replace it. When you first get a new switch you have to slot the power supplies into place. They can take more than one power supply for redundancy.
    </p>

